{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17636760","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17636760"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:34:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:34:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17604"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17604","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17604"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.14,0.62,0.1,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10318"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71513"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10318","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10318"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17604"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57022"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10031"},{"type":"tags","id":"10033"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24127"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24132"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71513","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71513"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe brush border of the small intestine contains numerous enzymes that are essential for the final stages of digestion.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the location of brush border enzymes?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Secreted into the intestinal lumen","Stored in secretory vesicles of goblet cells","Embedded in the luminal membrane of intestinal epithelial cells","Located within intestinal epithelial cell cytoplasm","Released by enteroendocrine cells"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EBrush border enzymes are \u003Cstrong\u003Eembedded in the luminal membrane of intestinal epithelial cells\u003C/strong\u003E. These membrane-bound enzymes include disaccharidases (lactase, sucrase, maltase) and peptidases that complete the final stages of carbohydrate and protein digestion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESecreted into the intestinal lumen\u003C/strong\u003E - Unlike pancreatic enzymes, brush border enzymes remain attached to the cell membrane\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELocated within intestinal epithelial cell cytoplasm\u003C/strong\u003E - These enzymes must be on the cell surface to access their substrates in the intestinal lumen\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStored in secretory vesicles of goblet cells\u003C/strong\u003E - Goblet cells produce and secrete mucus, not digestive enzymes\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReleased by enteroendocrine cells\u003C/strong\u003E - Enteroendocrine cells secrete hormones, not digestive enzymes\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe membrane location of these enzymes allows them to efficiently process nutrients in close proximity to their corresponding transport proteins, facilitating absorption of the breakdown products.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Brush border enzymes are located on the luminal surface of small intestinal epithelial cells and break down specific nutrients.","Lactase, sucrase, and maltase break down disaccharides into monosaccharides for absorption.","Peptidases in the brush border break down small peptides into amino acids."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57022"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17604"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57022","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57022"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-18T20:37:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-18T20:38:14+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10318"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71513"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4928"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udca9","name":"Gastrointestinal","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:50:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGr